dbo:abstract.@value: AI Explainability 360 is an open source toolkit by IBM.

In computer programming, a software framework is an abstraction in which software providing generic functionality can be selectively changed by additional user-written code, thus providing application-specific software.
A black box model is a complicated model that people is not easily able to understand. An example of black box model are the deep neural networks.
A model is a function that takes features as input and predicts labels as output. An explanation can be for understand the model or the data.
A classifier is a model that predicts categorical labels from features.
A consumer is a human receiving an explanation.
A directly interpretable model is a model that consumers can usually understand, such as a simple decision tree or Boolean rule set.

A post hoc explanation is an explanation coming from a model that approximates a black box model. The experts that differentiate the terms explanation and interpretation limit the term explanation only to post hoc explanation.

A loan application is used by borrowers to apply for a loan. Through the loan application, borrowers reveal key details about their finances to the lender. The loan application is crucial to determining whether the lender will grant the request for funds or credit.

An explanation is a reason or justification for the predicted label. Some experts differentiate explanations from interpretations. Explanations come from surrogate models and interpretations come from the models themselves.
A Disentangled representation is a representation in which changes to one feature leave other features unchanged.
A feature is an individual measurable property or characteristic.

A global explanation is an explanation for an entire model. Global explanations about entire models are most appropriate for data scientist, regulators and decision makers such as physicians, loan officiers and judges.

my:understand.@value: Global explanations are used to understand models.

dbo:abstract.@value: A label is a value indicating the outcome or category for a sample.
A local explanation is an explanation for a sample. Local explanations about individual samples are most appropriate for affected users such as patients, applicants and defendants.

my:understand.@value: Local explanation are used to understand models

dbo:abstract: An Artificial Neural Network (ANN) is a Machine Learning algorithm that can be trained to solve a given problem. A trained ANN is said to be a black box, this means that it is not always possible to exactly know its inner logic. ANNs are used because in practice they work very well, but not always.
rdfs:label: Artificial Neural Network

dbo:abstract.@value: Machine learning is a general approach for determining models from data.
A modality is the type of data, such as tabular data, images, audio signals, or natural language text.
Data are characteristics or information, usually numerical, that are collected through observation.
A persona is the role of the consumer, such as a decision maker, regulator, data scientist, or patient.
A prototype is a sample that exhibits the essence of a dataset.
A sample is a single data point, instance, or example.
A regressor is a model that predicts numerical labels from features.
A representation is a mathematical transformation of data into features suitable for models.
Score is a continuous valued output from a classifier. Applying a threshold to a score results in a predicted label.
Supervised learning refers to determining models from data having features and labels.
Training data is a dataset from which a model is learned.
Unsupervised learning refers to determining models or representations from data having only features, no labels.

The Contrastive Explanations Method (CEM) is an algorithm that tries to find the minimally sufficient changes to the input (of an automated process like an Artificial Neural Network) that can change the output. Sometimes CEM is not able to find these minimally sufficient changes, but it can go close to that.

rdfs:label: Algorithm
dbo:abstract: An algorithm is a finite sequence of instructions tipically to solve a class of problems or to perform a computation.

dbo:abstract.@value: Protodash provides exemplar-based explanations for summarizing datasets as well as explaining predictions made by an AI model. It employs a fast gradient based algorithm to find prototypes along with their (non-negative) importance weights. The algorithm minimizes the maximum mean discrepancy metric and has constant factor approximation guarantees for this weakly submodular function.

TED is an explainability framework that leverages domain-relevant explanations in the training dataset to predict both labels and explanations for new instances. The simplest instantiation of TED is called the Cartesian Product.
Learns a small, interpretable Boolean rule in disjunctive normal form (DNF) for binary classification.
Learns a reweighting of the training set based on a given interpretable model and a high-performing complex neural network.
Generalized Linear Rule Models (GLRM) learns a linear combination of conjunctions for real-valued regression through a generalized linear model (GLM) link function.
Contrastive Explanations Method with Monotonic Attribute Functions (CEM-MAF) creates contrastive explanations for complex images like CEM but based on high-level semantically meaningful attributes.
Disentangled Inferred Prior (DIP) Variational Autoencoder (VAE) learns high-level independent features from images that possibly have semantic interpretation.
Pertinent Positive (PP) is what is minimally sufficient to make positive an outcome. PPs are used by CEM algorithms to produce explanations.
Pertinent Negative (PN) is what is necessarily absent to make negative an outcome. PNs are used by CEM algorithms to produce explanations.

An algorithm for producing explanations Based on Samples uses a set of available examples to produce the explanation. If something unknown is similar to one of the available examples, than it has the same properties of those examples. An algorithm Based on Samples, is in terms of prototypes and criticisms, a form of case-based reasoning.
An algorithm for producing explanations Based on Features highlight features that are necessarily present or absent for an outcome to occur.
An algorithm for producing Elicited explanations uses (ad-hoc) domain-relevant explanations made by humans, to predict both labels and explanations for new unknown instances.
The FICO HELOC dataset contains anonymized information about home equity line of credit (HELOC) applications made by real homeowners.

dbo:abstract: A dataset is a collection of data.
rdfs:label: Dataset

dbo:abstract.@value: Home equity line of credit is a loan in which the lender agrees to lend a maximum amount within an agreed period, where the collateral is the borrower's equity in his/her house. HELOC funds can be borrowed during the 'draw period' (typically 5 to 25 years). Repayment is of the amount drawn amount plus interest. A HELOC may have a minimum monthly payment requirement (often 'interest only').

The «Consolidated risk markers» are an external estimate of the risk that you might not pay back the loan. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value for the external risk estimate, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

The «Age of oldest account in months» is the number of months that passed since your oldest trade was opened. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the age of oldest account in months, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Age of oldest account in months

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Age of most recent account in months» is the number of months passed since your most recent trade was opened. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the age of most recent account in months, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Age of most recent account in months

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Average age of accounts in months» is the average age of your credit accounts, in months. The older are your credit accounts, the greater is the «Average age of accounts in months». To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the average age of accounts in months, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Average age of accounts in months

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Number of satisfactory accounts» is the number of credit accounts having trades that were paid in full and closed with no negative information. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of satisfactory accounts, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

The «Number of accounts ever delinquent by 60 days or more» is the number of your credit accounts having trades that were more than 60 days late, and that were ever recorded in the derogatory public record. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of accounts ever delinquent by 60 days or more, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of accounts ever delinquent by 60 days or more

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Number of accounts ever delinquent by 90 days or more» is the number of your credit accounts having trades that were more than 90 days late, and that were ever recorded in the derogatory public record. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of accounts ever delinquent by 90 days or more, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of accounts ever delinquent by 90 days or more

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Percentage of accounts that were never delinquent» is the percentage of your credit accounts having trades that were never paid late. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the percentage of accounts that were never delinquent, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Percentage of accounts that were never delinquent

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Months since most recent delinquency» is the number of months that passed since your most recent deliquency (unpaid bill, etc..). To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the months since most recent delinquency, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

The «Worst delinquency score from last 12 months of public record» is the longest number of months (recorded in the public records during the last 12 months) that passed without you paying a bill, etc.. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the worst delinquency score from last 12 months of public record, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Worst delinquency score from last 12 months of public record

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Worst delinquency score ever» is the longest number of months that passed without you paying a bill, etc.. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the worst delinquency score ever, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

The «Total number of accounts» is the number of credit accounts you have. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the total number of accounts, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

The «Number of accounts opened in last 12 months» is the number of credit accounts you have opened in the last 12 months. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of accounts opened in last 12 months, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of accounts opened in last 12 months

dbo:abstract.@value: To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the percentage of accounts that are installment debt, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Percentage of accounts that are installment debt

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Months since most recent credit inquiry not within the last 7 days» is the number of months passed since your most recent inquiry (excluded the inquiries performed in the last 7 days). Excluding the last 7 days removes inquiries that are likely due to price comparision shopping. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the months since most recent credit inquiry not within the last 7 days, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Months since most recent credit inquiry not within the last 7 days

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Number of credit inquiries in last 6 months» is the number of inquiries you performed in the last 6 months. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of credit inquiries in last 6 months, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of credit inquiries in last 6 months

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Number of credit inquiries in last 6 months excluding the last 7 days» is the number of inquiries you performed in the last 6 months (excluded those in the last 7 days). Excluding the last 7 days removes inquiries that are likely due to price comparision shopping. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of credit inquiries in last 6 months excluding the last 7 days, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of credit inquiries in last 6 months excluding the last 7 days

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Revolving debt (e.g. credit card) balance as a percentage of credit limit» is the net fraction of revolving burden. This is revolving balance (balance from revolving trades) divided by credit limit. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the revolving debt (e.g. credit card) balance as a percentage of credit limit, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Revolving debt (e.g. credit card) balance as a percentage of credit limit

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Installment debt (e.g. car loan) balance as a percentage of original loan amount» is the net fraction of installment burden. This is the installment balance (balance from installment trades) divided by the original loan amount. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the installment debt (e.g. car loan) balance as a percentage of original loan amount, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Installment debt (e.g. car loan) balance as a percentage of original loan amount

dbo:abstract.@value: To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of revolving debt accounts with a balance, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of revolving debt accounts with a balance

dbo:abstract.@value: To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of installment debt accounts with a balance, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of installment debt accounts with a balance

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Number of accounts with high utilization» is the number of bank/national trades with high utilization ratio. To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the number of accounts with high utilization, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Number of accounts with high utilization

dbo:abstract.@value: To every customer (included you) has been associated a value indicating the percentage of accounts with a balance, and this value is used to compute the FICO Score and to decide whether to assign the loan.

rdfs:label: Percentage of accounts with a balance

dbo:abstract.@value: The «Risk Performance» is the likelihood that you will pay back your loan, as agreed. For every individual that requires a loan, the Risk Performance is predicted by using relevant features that identify the individual, such as: the consolidated risk markers, the number of satisfactory trades, etc..
A delinquency is a failure to deliver even the minimum payment on a loan or debt payment on or before the time agreed.
An inquiry is an item on a consumer's credit report that shows that someone with a permissible purpose has previously requested a copy of the consumer's report.
Higher values of monotonically decreasing features imply a lower probability of receiving the loan.
Higher values of monotonically increasing features imply a greater probability of receiving the loan.
Risk is the likelihood that an individual will pay his or her credit obligations as agreed.

Installment trades are trades where borrowers repay the loan with scheduled, periodic payments. This type of credit involves the gradual reduction of principal and eventual full repayment, ending the credit cycle.

Trade, or commerce, involves the transfer of the ownership of goods or services, from one person or entity to another, in exchange for money, goods or services. A network that allows trade is called a market.
Revolving trade are trade that allow borrowers to use a line of credit according to the terms of the contract, which do not have fixed payments.
Derogatory public record is a negative information on your credit report that is of a more serious nature and has become a matter of public record.
Derogatory records are any negative information on you credit report that lowers your credit scoring. The record can be a minor issue or a more serious concern.

Business process automation (BPA), also known as business automation or digital transformation, is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes. It can streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs. It consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.

A line of credit is a preset borrowing limit that can be used at any time. The borrower can take money out as needed until the limit is reached, and as money is repaid, it can be borrowed again in the case of an open line of credit.
